05107nam a22008055i 9780823294534DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232945347 a10.1515/97808232945342doi  a(DE-B1597)577373  a(OCoLC)1257763281  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN1076b.K89 2021 7aLIT0190002bisacsh04a809.1/935432231 aKuzner, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Form of Love :bPoetry's Quarrel with Philosophy /cJames Kuzner. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Form of Love Poetry, Philosophy, and the Closeness of Loving Reading -- t1. Disjunctive Love: Philosophical Project and Poetic Experience in Donne's "Th e Ecstasy" -- t2. Obscure Love: Virtual Masochisms in Philips's "Friendship's Mysterys" -- t3. Forgetting to Love: Problems of Praise in Herbert's "Th e Flower" -- t4. Loving Rhyme: Reading Mastery in Crashaw's "Th e Flaming Heart" -- t5. Green Love: Lost in Marvell's "Th e Garden" -- t6. Love and/or Lyric: Dickinson's "I cannot live with You -" -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCan poetry articulate something about love that philosophy cannot? The Form of Love argues that it can. In close readings of seven "metaphysical" poems, the book shows how poets of the early modern period and beyond use poetic form to turn philosophy to other ends, in order not to represent the truth about love but to create a virtual experience of love, in all its guises. The Form of Love shows how verse creates love that can't exist without poetry's specific affordances, and how poems can, in their impossibility, prompt love's radical re-imagining. Like the philosophies on which they draw, metaphysical poems imagine love as an intense form of non-sovereignty, of giving up control. They even imagine love as a liberating bondage-to a friend, a beloved, a saint, a God, or a garden. Yet these poems create strange, striking versions of such love, made in, rather than through, the devices, structures, and forces where love appears.Tracing how poems think, Kuzner argues, requires an intimate form of reading: close-even too close-attention to and thinking with the text. Showing how poetry thinks of love otherwise than other fields, the book reveals how poetry and philosophy can nevertheless enter into a relation that is itself like love.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aLove in literature. 0aLove poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aLovexPhilosophyxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aForm.  aLove.  aMetaphysical Poetry.  aPhilosophy of Love.  aPoetics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073909140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823294534zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823294534423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823294534/original  a978-3-11-073909-1  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 English